We now again look at the case where the observations that the human observes are known to the reward learning system, as in Section D.2. Furthermore, we assume that \(\mathbf{B}:\mathds{R}^{\mathcal{S}}\to\mathds{R}^{\widehat{\Omega}}\) is such that \(\ker\mathbf{B}\cap\operatorname{im}\mathbf{\Gamma}=\{0\}\). In this case, we can apply Corollary D.4 and identify the true return function \(G\) from \(\mathbf{B}(G)\), which, in turn, can be identified up to an additive constant from the observation-based choice probabilities with the argument as for Proposition 3.1.

In this section, we investigate what happens when the human belief model is slightly misspecified. In other words: the learning system uses a perturbed matrix \(\mathbf{B}_{\bm{\Delta}}\coloneqq\mathbf{B}+\bm{\Delta}\) with some small perturbation \(\bm{\Delta}\). How much will the inferred return function deviate from the truth? To answer this, we first need to outline some norm theory of linear operators.

#### d.6.1 Some Norm Theory for Linear Operators

In this section, let \(V,W\) be two finite-dimensional inner product-spaces. In other words, \(V\) and \(W\) each have inner products \(\left\langle\cdot,\cdot\right\rangle\) and there are linear isomorphisms \(V\cong\mathds{R}^{k}\), \(W\cong\mathds{R}^{m}\) such that the inner products in \(V\) and \(W\) correspond to the standard scalar products in \(\mathds{R}^{k}\) and \(\mathds{R}^{m}\). The reason that we don't directly work with \(\mathds{R}^{k}\) and \(\mathds{R}^{m}\) itself is that we will later apply the analysis to the case that \(V=\operatorname{im}\mathbf{\Gamma}\subseteq\mathds{R}^{\mathcal{S}}\). Let in this whole section \(\mathbf{A}:V\to W\) be a linear operator and \(\bm{\Delta}:V\to W\) be a perturbance, so that \(\mathbf{A}_{\bm{\Delta}}\coloneqq\mathbf{A}+\bm{\Delta}\) is a perturbed version of \(\mathbf{A}\).

The inner products give rise to a norm on \(V\) and \(W\) defined by

\[\left\|v\right\|=\sqrt{\left\langle v,v\right\rangle},\quad\left\|w\right\|= \sqrt{\left\langle w,w\right\rangle}.\]

As is well known, for each linear operator \(\mathbf{A}:V\to W\) there exists a unique, basis-independent _adjoint_ (generalizing the notion of a transpose) \(\mathbf{A}^{T}:W\to V\) such that for all \(v\in V\) and \(w\in W\), we have

\[\left\langle\mathbf{A}\,v,w\right\rangle=\left\langle v,\mathbf{A}^{T}\,w \right\rangle.\]

Let us recall the following fact that is often used in linear regression:

**Lemma D.16**.: _Assume \(\mathbf{A}:V\to W\) is injective. Then \(\mathbf{A}^{T}\,\mathbf{A}:V\to V\) is invertible and \((\mathbf{A}^{T}\,\mathbf{A})^{-1}\,\mathbf{A}^{T}\) is a left inverse of \(\mathbf{A}\)._

Proof.: To show that \(\mathbf{A}^{T}\,\mathbf{A}\) is invertible, we only need to show that it is injective. Thus, let \(0\neq x\in V\). Then

\[\left\langle x,\mathbf{A}^{T}\,\mathbf{A}\,x\right\rangle=\left\langle\mathbf{ A}\,x,\mathbf{A}\,x\right\rangle=\left\|\,\mathbf{A}\,x\right\|^{2}>0,\]

where the last step followed from the injectivity of \(\mathbf{A}\). Thus, \(\mathbf{A}^{T}\,\mathbf{A}\,x\neq 0\), and so \(\mathbf{A}^{T}\,\mathbf{A}\) is injective, and thus invertible. Consequently, \((\mathbf{A}^{T}\,\mathbf{A})^{-1}\,\mathbf{A}^{T}\) is a well-defined operator. That it is the left inverse of \(\mathbf{A}\) is clear. 

**Definition D.17** (Operator Norm).: _The norm of an operator \(\mathbf{A}:V\to W\) is given by_

\[\left\|\,\mathbf{A}\,\right\|\coloneqq\max_{x,\;\left\|x\right\|=1}\,\|\, \mathbf{A}\,x\|.\]

_It has the following well-known properties, where \(\mathbf{A},\mathbf{B}\) and \(\mathbf{C}\) are matrices of compatible sizes:_

\[\left\|\,\mathbf{A}+\mathbf{B}\,\right\|\leq\left\|\,\mathbf{A}\,\right\|+ \left\|\,\mathbf{B}\,\right\|,\quad\left\|\,\mathbf{C}\,\mathbf{A}\,\right\| \leq\left\|\,\mathbf{C}\,\right\|\cdot\left\|\,\mathbf{A}\,\right\|,\quad\left\| \,\mathbf{A}^{T}\,\right\|=\left\|\,\mathbf{A}\,\right\|.\]

To study how a perturbance in \(\mathbf{A}\) (and thus \(\mathbf{A}^{T}\,\mathbf{A}\)) transfers into a perturbance of \(\left(\,\mathbf{A}^{T}\,\mathbf{A}\,\right)^{-1}\), we will use the following theorem:

**Theorem D.18** (El Ghaoui (2002)).: _Let \(\mathbf{B}:V\to V\) be an invertible operator. Let \(\rho<\|\,\mathbf{B}^{-1}\,\|^{-1}\). Let \(\mathbf{\Delta}:V\to V\) be any operator with \(\|\,\mathbf{\Delta}\,\|\leq\rho\). Then \(\mathbf{B}+\mathbf{\Delta}\) is invertible and we have_

\[\left\|(\mathbf{B}+\mathbf{\Delta})^{-1}-\mathbf{B}^{-1}\,\right\|\leq\frac{ \rho\cdot\|\,\mathbf{B}^{-1}\,\|}{\|\,\mathbf{B}^{-1}\,\|^{-1}-\rho}.\]

Proof.: See El Ghaoui (2002), Section 7 and in particular Equation 7.2. Note that the reference defines \(\|\,\mathbf{A}\,\|\) to be the largest singular value of \(\mathbf{A}\); by the well-known min-max theorem, this is equivalent to Definition D.17. 

We will apply this theorem to \(\mathbf{A}^{T}\,\mathbf{A}\), which raises the question about the size of the perturbance in \(\mathbf{A}^{T}\,\mathbf{A}\) for a given perturbance in \(\mathbf{A}\). This is clarified in the following lemma. Before stating it, for a given perturbance \(\rho\), define

\[\widetilde{\rho}(\mathbf{A})\coloneqq\rho\cdot\big{(}2\cdot\|\,\mathbf{A}\, \|+\rho\big{)},\]

which depends on \(\mathbf{A}\) and \(\rho\). Also, recall that for a given perturbance \(\mathbf{\Delta}\), we define \(\mathbf{A}_{\mathbf{\Delta}}\coloneqq\mathbf{A}+\mathbf{\Delta}\). We obtain:

**Lemma D.19**.: _Assume that \(\|\,\mathbf{\Delta}\,\|\leq\rho\). Then_

\[\|\,\mathbf{A}_{\mathbf{\Delta}}^{T}\,\mathbf{A}_{\mathbf{\Delta}}-\mathbf{A} ^{T}\,\mathbf{A}\,\|\leq\widetilde{\rho}(\mathbf{A}).\]

Proof.: We have

\[\big{\|}\,\mathbf{A}_{\mathbf{\Delta}}^{T}\,\mathbf{A}_{\mathbf{ \Delta}}-\mathbf{A}^{T}\,\mathbf{A}\,\big{\|} =\big{\|}(\mathbf{A}+\mathbf{\Delta})^{T}(\mathbf{A}+\mathbf{ \Delta})-\mathbf{A}^{T}\,\mathbf{A}\,\big{\|}\] \[=\big{\|}\,\mathbf{A}^{T}\,\mathbf{\Delta}+\mathbf{\Delta}^{T}\, \mathbf{A}+\mathbf{\Delta}^{T}\,\mathbf{\Delta}\,\big{\|}\] \[\leq\|\,\mathbf{A}\,\|\cdot\|\,\mathbf{\Delta}\,\|+\|\,\mathbf{ \Delta}\,\|\cdot\|\,\mathbf{A}\,\|+\|\,\mathbf{\Delta}\,\|^{2}\] \[\leq\rho\cdot\Big{(}2\cdot\|\,\mathbf{A}\,\|+\rho\Big{)}\] \[=\widetilde{\rho}(\mathbf{A}).\]

To be able to apply Theorem D.18 to \(\mathbf{A}^{T}\,\mathbf{A}\), we need to make sure that \(\widetilde{\rho}(\mathbf{A})\) is bounded above by \(\big{\|}(\mathbf{A}^{T}\,\mathbf{A}\,\big{)}^{-1}\big{\|}^{-1}\). The next lemma clarifies what condition \(\rho\) needs to satisfy for \(\widetilde{\rho}(\mathbf{A})\) to obey that bound. For this, define

\[\tau(\mathbf{A})\coloneqq-\|\,\mathbf{A}\,\|+\sqrt{\|\,\mathbf{A}\,\|^{2}+ \big{\|}(\mathbf{A}^{T}\,\mathbf{A})^{-1}\big{\|}^{-1}},\] (9)

which only depends on \(\mathbf{A}\).

**Lemma D.20**.: _Assume \(\rho<\tau(\mathbf{A})\). Then_

\[\widetilde{\rho}(\mathbf{A})<\big{\|}(\mathbf{A}^{T}\,\mathbf{A})^{-1}\big{\|} ^{-1}.\]

Proof.: Note that \(\rho=\tau(\mathbf{A})\) is the positive solution to the following quadratic equation in the indeterminate \(\rho\):

\[\rho^{2}+2\cdot\|\,\mathbf{A}\,\|\cdot\rho-\big{\|}(\mathbf{A}^{T}\,\mathbf{A })^{-1}\big{\|}^{-1}=\widetilde{\rho}(\mathbf{A})-\big{\|}(\mathbf{A}^{T}\, \mathbf{A})^{-1}\big{\|}^{-1}=0.\]

Since this is a convex parabola, we get the inequality \(\widetilde{\rho}(\mathbf{A})-\big{\|}(\mathbf{A}^{T}\,\mathbf{A})^{-1}\big{\|} ^{-1}<0\) whenever we have \(0\leq\rho<\tau(\mathbf{A})\), which shows the result. 

Finally, we put it all together to obtain a bound on the perturbance of \(\big{(}\,\mathbf{A}^{T}\,\mathbf{A}\,\big{)}^{-1}\,\mathbf{A}^{T}\). For this, set

\[C(\mathbf{A},\rho)\coloneqq\frac{\widetilde{\rho}(\mathbf{A})\cdot\Big{\|} \big{(}\,\mathbf{A}^{T}\,\mathbf{A}\,\big{)}^{-1}\Big{\|}}{\Big{\|}\big{(}\, \mathbf{A}^{T}\,\mathbf{A}\,\big{)}^{-1}\Big{\|}^{-1}-\widetilde{\rho}( \mathbf{A})}\cdot\Big{(}\big{\|}\,\mathbf{A}\,\big{\|}+\rho\Big{)}+\Big{\|} \big{(}\,\mathbf{A}^{T}\,\mathbf{A}\,\big{)}^{-1}\Big{\|}\cdot\rho.\] (10)

We obtain:

**Proposition D.21**.: _Assume \(\left\|\,\bm{\Delta}\,\right\|\leq\rho<\tau(\bm{\Lambda})\). Then \(\mathbf{A}_{\bm{\Delta}}^{T}\,\mathbf{A}_{\bm{\Delta}}\) is invertible, and we have_

\[\left\|\left(\,\mathbf{A}_{\bm{\Delta}}^{T}\,\mathbf{A}_{\bm{\Delta}}\,\right)^ {-1}\,\mathbf{A}_{\bm{\Delta}}^{T}-\left(\,\mathbf{A}^{T}\,\mathbf{A}\,\right)^ {-1}\,\mathbf{A}^{T}\,\right\|\leq C(\mathbf{A},\rho).\]

Proof.: The invertibility of \(\mathbf{A}_{\bm{\Delta}}^{T}\,\mathbf{A}_{\bm{\Delta}}\) follows from Theorem D.18, Lemma D.19 and Lemma D.20. We get

\[\left\|\left(\,\mathbf{A}_{\bm{\Delta}}^{T}\,\mathbf{A}_{\bm{ \Delta}}\,\right)^{-1}\,\mathbf{A}_{\bm{\Delta}}^{T}-\left(\,\mathbf{A}^{T}\, \mathbf{A}\,\right)^{-1}\,\mathbf{A}^{T}\,\right\|\] \[=\] \[= C(\mathbf{A},\rho).\]

In the second-to-last step, we used Theorem D.18. 

The constant \(C(\mathbf{A},\rho)\), defined in Equation (10), has a fairly complicated form. In the following proposition, we find an easier-to-study upper bound in a special case:

**Proposition D.22**.: _Assume that \(\rho\leq\left\|\,\mathbf{A}\,\right\|\) and \(\rho\leq-\left\|\,\mathbf{A}\,\right\|+\sqrt{\left\|\,\mathbf{A}\,\right\|^{ 2}+1/2\cdot\left\|(\mathbf{A}^{T}\,\mathbf{A})^{-1}\right\|^{-1}}\).3 Then we have_

