In this section, we clarify \(\operatorname{im}\boldsymbol{\Gamma}\) and \(\ker\mathbf{B}\) in special cases, as their intersection is the crucial ambiguity in Theorem D.2.

The following proposition shows that for deterministic \(P_{\vec{G}}\) and a rational human, \(\ker\mathbf{B}\) decomposes into hyperplanes defined by normal vectors of probabilities of sequences mapping to the same observation sequence:

**Proposition D.25**.: _Assume the human reasons as in Section D.1. Assume \(P_{\vec{G}}\) is deterministic. Let \(B(\vec{s})\) be the distribution of sequences under the human's belief over the policy, given by \(B(\vec{s})=\int_{\pi^{\prime}}B(\pi^{\prime})P^{\pi^{\prime}}(\vec{s})\) for some policy prior \(B(\pi^{\prime})\). For each \(\vec{o}\), let \(B_{\vec{o}}\coloneqq[B(\vec{s})]_{\vec{s}\colon\vec{G}(\vec{s})=\vec{o}}\in \mathds{R}^{\{\vec{s}\in\mathcal{S}\mid\vec{G}(\vec{s})=\vec{o}\}}\) be the vector of probabilities of sequences that are observed as \(\vec{o}\)._

_Let \(G^{\prime}\) be a return function. For each \(\vec{o}\in\vec{\Omega}\), define the restriction \(G^{\prime}_{\vec{o}}\in\mathds{R}^{\{\vec{s}\in\mathcal{S}|\vec{G}(\vec{s})= \vec{o}\}}\) by \(G^{\prime}_{\vec{o}}(\vec{s})\coloneqq G^{\prime}(\vec{s})\) for all \(\vec{s}\in\{\vec{s}\in\vec{\mathcal{S}}\mid\vec{G}(\vec{s})=\vec{o}\}\). Assume that \(B(\vec{s}\mid\vec{o})\) is the Bayesian posterior. Then \(G^{\prime}\in\ker\mathbf{B}\) if and only if the property_

\[B_{\vec{o}}\cdot G^{\prime}_{\vec{o}}=0\]

_holds for all \(\vec{o}\in\vec{\Omega}\)._

Proof.: For a deterministic observation kernel \(P_{\vec{G}}\), by Bayes rule we have

\[B(\vec{s}\mid\vec{o}) =\frac{P_{\vec{G}}(\vec{o}\mid\vec{s})\cdot B(\vec{s})}{\sum_{\vec {s}^{\prime}}P_{\vec{G}}(\vec{o}\mid\vec{s}^{\prime})\cdot B(\vec{s}^{\prime})}\] \[=\frac{\delta_{\vec{o}}\big{(}\vec{G}(\vec{s})\big{)}\cdot B(\vec {s})}{\sum_{\vec{s}^{\prime}}\delta_{\vec{o}}\big{(}\vec{G}(\vec{s}^{\prime}) \big{)}\cdot B(\vec{s}^{\prime})}\] \[=\begin{cases}0,\ \vec{\mathcal{O}}(\vec{s})\neq\vec{o}\\ \frac{B(\vec{s})}{\sum_{\vec{s}^{\prime}\colon\vec{G}(\vec{s}^{\prime})=\vec{ o}}B(\vec{s}^{\prime})},\ \vec{O}(\vec{s})=\vec{o}.\end{cases}\]

Thus, for any return function \(G^{\prime}\) and any observation sequence \(\vec{o}\), we have

\[\big{[}\,\mathbf{B}(G^{\prime})\big{]}(\vec{o}) =\underset{\vec{s}\sim B(\vec{s}\mid\vec{o})}{\mathbf{E}}\big{[}G ^{\prime}(\vec{s})\big{]}\] \[=\sum_{\vec{s}}B(\vec{s}\mid\vec{o})G^{\prime}(\vec{s})\] \[=\sum_{\vec{s}\colon\vec{G}(\vec{s})=\vec{o}}\frac{B(\vec{s})}{ \sum_{\vec{s}^{\prime}\colon\vec{G}(\vec{s}^{\prime})=\vec{o}}B(\vec{s}^{ \prime})}G^{\prime}(\vec{s})\] \[=\Bigg{(}\sum_{\vec{s}^{\prime}\colon\vec{G}(\vec{s}^{\prime})= \vec{o}}B(\vec{s}^{\prime})\Bigg{)}^{-1}\cdot\sum_{\vec{s}\colon\vec{G}(\vec{ s})=\vec{o}}B(\vec{s})G^{\prime}(\vec{s}).\]

Thus, we have \(G^{\prime}\in\ker\mathbf{B}\) if and only if

\[B_{\vec{o}}\cdot G^{\prime}_{\vec{o}}=\sum_{\vec{s}\colon\vec{G}(\vec{s})= \vec{o}}B(\vec{s})G^{\prime}(\vec{s})=0\]

for all \(\vec{o}\). That was to show. 

